Your manager is raising two very valid enterprise architecture concerns. In fact, these are common criticisms of a naive RFC 8693 design.


---

Problem 1: Authorization Server is a Single Point of Failure

Current flow:

Proxy
   │
RFC 8693
   ▼
Authorization Server
   │
New Token
   ▼
Digital Agent

If the Authorization Server is down:

❌ No new tokens

❌ No agent communication

❌ Entire platform stops


For a banking platform, that's unacceptable.


---

Problem 2: Token Exchange on Every Request

Imagine:

1000 requests/sec

Current design:

1000 Token Exchanges/sec
+
1000 Agent Calls/sec

You're effectively doubling the load.

Latency becomes:

Client
  ↓
Gateway
  ↓
Proxy
  ↓
Authorization Server
  ↓
Proxy
  ↓
Digital Agent

Instead of:

Client
  ↓
Gateway
  ↓
Proxy
  ↓
Digital Agent

This adds an extra network round trip to every request.


---

Enterprise Solution (What Google, Microsoft, Banks do)

Instead of exchanging a token per request, exchange per session or cache window.

External App
      │
OAuth2
      ▼
Proxy
      │
      │
Does cached delegated token exist?
      │
 ┌────┴─────┐
 │          │
Yes        No
 │          │
 │     RFC8693
 │          │
 │    Authorization Server
 │          │
 └────┬─────┘
      │
Cached Token
      │
      ▼
Digital Agent


---

Cache the Delegated Token

Instead of:

Request 1 → RFC8693

Request 2 → RFC8693

Request 3 → RFC8693

Do:

Request 1

↓

RFC8693

↓

Token valid for 5 mins

↓

Use same token

↓

Request 2

↓

Request 3

↓

Request 4

↓

After expiry

↓

Exchange again

Latency becomes almost zero after the first exchange.


