---

Even Better (Large Enterprises)

Many banks avoid RFC 8693 for every internal hop.

They use:

SPIFFE + mTLS for authenticating workloads.

The original OAuth token is propagated unchanged or transformed once at the edge.

Authorization decisions are enforced locally (e.g., by OPA or service-specific policies).


RFC 8693 is then used only when the downstream service genuinely needs a different identity or a reduced scope, not for every call between every pair of services.


---

What I would recommend for your project

For your architecture, a balanced enterprise design is:

External App → API Gateway → OAuth2/OIDC

API Gateway validates the user token once.

Digital Agent Access Proxy checks OPA policies.

RFC 8693 is used only when a different delegated scope is actually required, and delegated tokens are cached for their short lifetime.

Internal service-to-service authentication uses SPIFFE + mTLS.

Authorization Server is deployed as a highly available cluster behind a load balancer.


This addresses both of your manager's concerns:

No single point of failure (HA Authorization Server).

Minimal latency (token caching and selective token exchange instead of per-request exchanges).
